#Approach:

Approach:
Ye code monotonic decreasing stack use karta hai, jisme indices store hote hain.
Har day ke liye hum left side me nearest greater price wala index dhundte hain.

1. Day 0 ka span hamesha 1 hoga, isliye s[0] = 1.
2. Stack me indices store kiye jaate hain.
3. Current price se chhote ya equal price wale sab indices stack se pop kar dete hain,
   kyuki wo current day ka answer nahi ban sakte.
4. Agar stack empty ho gaya, iska matlab left me koi greater element nahi hai,
   to span = i + 1.
5. Agar stack empty nahi hai, to top par nearest greater element ka index hai,
   to span = i - stack.peek().
6. Fir current index ko stack me push kar dete hain future days ke liye.

Main idea:
Stack hamesha aise indices rakhta hai jinke prices decreasing order me hote hain.
Isse har element mostly ek hi baar push-pop hota hai, isliye solution efficient hai.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

#Code:

import java.util.Deque;
import java.util.ArrayDeque;

public class Solution
{
    public static int[] calculateSpan(int price[], int n)
    {
        //You can code here

        Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();

        int[] s = new int[n];
        s[0] = 1;
        stack.push(0);

        for(int i=1; i<n; i++){
          while(!stack.isEmpty()){
            int top = stack.peek();
            if(price[top] > price[i]){
              break;
            }
            else{
              stack.pop();
            }
          }
          if(stack.isEmpty()){
            s[i] = i+1;
          }
          else{
            s[i] = i - stack.peek();
          }
          stack.push(i);
        }
        return s;
      

      
    }
}
